class:: WarpCh
summary:: Nonlinear warped filter based on the ChowDSP Warp module
categories:: UGens>Filters
related:: Guides/ChowDSPPorts

Description::

WarpCh follows the full ChowDSP Warp module control surface. The core is a nonlinear peaking-filter / feedback-loop structure whose internal coefficients are cooked from the user controls every few samples and then evaluated at fixed 2x oversampling. In DSP terms it is a delay-free nonlinear filter loop, so `cutoff`, `heat`, `width`, and `drive` all interact inside the same recursive structure instead of acting as cleanly separated stages.

That gives the effect a more unstable and expressive identity than a normal EQ or phaser. Depending on mode and drive it can sound like resonant coloration, narrow moving emphasis, or a more aggressive warped resonance that almost behaves like a self-excited filter body.

definitionlist::
## cutoff: || `0..1`, mapped exponentially to the internal filter frequency
## heat: || `0..1`, mapping depends on `mode`
## width: || `0..1`, mapping depends on `mode`
## drive: || `0..1`, mapping depends on `mode`
## mode: || discrete mapping selector `0`, `1`, or `2`
::

Internally, WarpCh preserves fixed 2x oversampling, the nonlinear peaking filter and delay-free feedback loop, the 16-sample parameter recook cadence, and the original short fade-in after mode changes.

classmethods::

method::ar

argument::in
Input signal.

argument::cutoff
Normalized cutoff control in `0..1`.

argument::heat
Normalized heat control in `0..1`.

argument::width
Normalized width control in `0..1`.

argument::drive
Normalized drive control in `0..1`.

argument::mode
Discrete mode selector. Values are quantized like the Rack module: `0`, `1`, or `2`.

argument::mul
Output multiplier.

argument::add
Output offset.


